# The POSIX wrapper MUST stay LF-terminated; CRLF would break the
# shebang on Linux clones and silently send the script through the
# wrong interpreter.
release/wrappers/project-issues text eol=lf

# The Windows wrapper is a batch file -- batch interpreters tolerate
# either line ending, but CRLF is conventional on Windows.
release/wrappers/project-issues.cmd text eol=crlf

# The release workflow copies release/wrappers/project-issues -> bin/project-issues
# and commits that to the orphan release branch. Without an explicit rule
# `core.autocrlf=true` re-introduces CRLF on the index-write, which breaks
# the shebang on Linux consumers (ticket #34).
bin/project-issues text eol=lf

# PyInstaller outputs MUST never be touched by EOL normalisation, even if
# someone's local core.autocrlf is misconfigured. The Linux binary has no
# .exe suffix so its binary nature isn't auto-detected from the extension.
bin/linux-x86_64/project-issues binary
bin/windows-x86_64/project-issues.exe binary
